{{Quote|In Basic, ''please''?|[[Garazeb Orrelios]]|<ref name="Wings of the Master">{{Rebels|Wings of the Master}}</ref>}}
'''Galactic Basic Standard''',<ref name="BMF 63">{{BuildFalconCite|63|Guide to the Galaxy}}</ref> also known as '''Galactic Basic''',<ref name="Character Encyclopedia">''[[Star Wars Character Encyclopedia: Updated and Expanded]]''</ref> '''Basic''',<ref name="Aliens of the Galaxy">''[[Star Wars: Aliens of the Galaxy]]''</ref> or '''galactic standard''',<ref name="HttJ">''[[Heir to the Jedi]]''</ref> was the name of the most prevalent [[language]] in [[the galaxy]].<ref name="Aliens of the Galaxy" /> It was spoken by [[species]] including&mdash;but not limited to&mdash;[[human]]s,<ref name="TPM">{{Film|I}}</ref> [[Pantoran]]s,<ref name="sweTA">{{SWE|groups|talz|Talz}}</ref> and [[Toydarian]]s,<ref name="TPM" /> but not by [[Ithorian]]s<ref name="R1VG">''[[Star Wars: Rogue One: The Ultimate Visual Guide]]''</ref> or [[Talz]].<ref name="sweTA" /> The [[Gungan]]s of [[Naboo]] spoke a [[Unidentified Gungan dialect|heavily accented dialect of Basic]], with many differences in grammar and vocabulary.<ref name="TPM" /> [[Diplodialect]] was a specific register of Basic used in the [[diplomat]]ic circles of the [[Galactic Republic]].<ref name="AIA">{{InsiderCite|186|An Innocent Abroad: The Rise and Prattfalls of Jar Jar Binks}}</ref>

Most [[stormtrooper]]s, the elite soldiers of the [[Galactic Empire]], could only speak and understand Basic, despite the commonness of other languages such as [[Huttese]].<ref name="ROR">''[[Rise of the Rebels]]''</ref> With vocal cords that were quite different from those of many other species, [[Wookiee]]s and Ithorians were entirely unable to speak Basic, though they could learn to understand it.<ref name="everything">''[[Star Wars: Absolutely Everything You Need to Know]]''</ref> Many Ithorians used [[translator collar]]s to simulate speaking Basic.<ref name="Empire Day (episode)">{{Rebels|Empire Day (episode)}}</ref> [[Tasu Leech]], leader of the [[Kanjiklub]], was unwilling to speak Basic, which he dismissed as a "soft language for soft people."<ref name="Tasu Leech">{{Databank|tasu-leech|Tasu Leech}}</ref> Basic could be written in several forms, including [[Aurebesh]], [[High Galactic]],<ref name="Propaganda">''[[Star Wars Propaganda: A History of Persuasive Art in the Galaxy]]''</ref>
and [[Outer Rim Basic]].<ref name="VE">''[[Star Wars: The Visual Encyclopedia]]''</ref>

==Accents==
Basic could also be spoken with a variety of accents. [[Imperial officer]] [[Piers Roddance]] spoke in a clipped and cultured manner that student [[Zare Leonis]] knew was a [[Core Worlds]] accent, or at least an imitation of one. His fellow student [[Merei Spanjaf]] also spoke with a Core Worlds accent due to her upbringing on the [[planet]] [[Corulag]].<ref name="Servants of the Empire">''[[Servants of the Empire: Edge of the Galaxy]]''</ref> The accents of individuals from other planets within the Core were also aristocratic, including the [[Chandrila]]n accent, as spoken by the [[droid]] [[R-K77]],<ref name="Empire's End">[[Aftermath: Empire's End (audiobook)|''Aftermath: Empire's End'' audiobook]]</ref> the accent of [[pilot]] [[Nash Windrider]] of [[Alderaan]],<ref name="Lost Stars">''[[Lost Stars]]''</ref> the clipped tones of [[Armitage Hux|Armitage]] and [[Brendol Hux]] of [[Arkanis]],<ref name="Phasmaaudiobook">[[Phasma (audiobook)|''Phasma'' audiobook]]</ref> and the [[Coruscant]]i accent as spoken by Coruscant natives [[Pax Maripher]]<ref name="Master and Apprentice">''[[Master & Apprentice]]''</ref> and [[Chassellon Stevis]].<ref name="LPOA">[[Leia, Princess of Alderaan (audiobook)|''Leia, Princess of Alderaan'' audiobook]]</ref> [[Captain]] [[Lorth Needa]] was an Imperial officer who spoke with a Core Worlds accent, which was mocked by his subordinate "[[Howlrunner (Theta Squadron)|Howlrunner]]."<ref name="TIE Pilot Survival">{{StoryCite|story=Amara Kel's Rules for TIE Pilot Survival (Probably)|book=From a Certain Point of View: The Empire Strikes Back|sformatted=Amara Kel's Rules for TIE Pilot Survival (Probably)}}</ref>

[[File:Takeyourdaughtertoworkday.png|thumb|left|300px|During her final conversation with Wilhuff Tarkin (left), Leia Organa (center) mocked the man's accent by imitating it.]]
The Coruscanti accent was that of the Imperial elite and their [[propaganda]] broadcasts, as well as Rebel satire. Imperial [[governor]] [[Everi Chalis]], a [[human]] originally from an impoverished colonial backwater, had a natural accent that was higher in pitch, with a subtle drawl, stretched vowels, and less enunciation than Coruscanti, but adopted what Imperial [[Captain]] [[Tabor Seitaron]] considered an awful, over-enunciated, and exaggerated "schoolgirl" Coruscanti accent while in the service of the Empire.<ref name="Twilight Company">[[Battlefront: Twilight Company (audiobook)|''Battlefront: Twilight Company'' audiobook]]</ref> [[Grand Moff]] [[Wilhuff Tarkin]], originally from the [[Outer Rim Territories|Outer Rim]] world [[Eriadu]], and many senior Imperial officers spoke with an aristocratic accent, which [[Princess]] [[Leia Skywalker Organa Solo|Leia Organa]] mockingly imitated during their final meeting.<ref name="Bloodline">[[Bloodline (novel)|''Bloodline'']]</ref> The criminal [[Bala-Tik]] spoke with the clipped tones of the Core Worlds, but with a harsher edge.<ref name="TFA dictionary">''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens: The Visual Dictionary]]''</ref>

The accent of the Outer Rim world [[Serenno]] was aristocratic and similar<ref name="Thrawn Alliances">[[Thrawn: Alliances (audiobook)|''Thrawn: Alliances'' audiobook]]</ref> to those of Chandrila<ref name="Empire's End" /> and Coruscant.<ref name="Master and Apprentice" /> The people of the Outer Rim planet [[Lothal]] typically spoke with an Outer Rim accent,<ref name="Rebel in the Ranks">''[[Servants of the Empire: Rebel in the Ranks]]''</ref> and Core Worlds accents were rarely heard there.<ref name="Servants of the Empire" /> Lothal native Governor [[Arihnda Pryce]] naturally spoke with such an accent,<ref name="Thrawn">[[Thrawn (novel)|''Thrawn'']]</ref> but like Chalis,<ref name="Twilight Company" /> adopted an aristocratic accent while serving the Empire.<ref name="Thrawn" /> [[Professor]] [[Sahali]] of the [[Republic Special Weapons Group]] spoke with a heavy Outer Rim accent.<ref name="Catalyst">''[[Catalyst: A Rogue One Novel]]''</ref>

[[File:DengarMocksTasu-BountyHunters24.png|thumb|right|300px|The pit fighter Tasu Leech spoke with a thick Nar Kanji accent.]]
[[Eli N. Vanto|Eli Vanto]] of the [[Wild Space]] world [[Lysatra]] spoke with a notable Wild Space accent that he was mocked for at the [[Royal Imperial Academy]] on Coruscant.<ref name="Thrawn" /> The accent of those native to the Outer Rim planet [[Pamarthe]] was thick and had the burr of it settle on the r's.<ref name="Bloodline" /> Pilot [[Norra Wexley]] spoke with a subtle [[Myrra]]n accent from her [[homeworld]]<ref name="Resistance Reborn">''[[Resistance Reborn]]''</ref> and [[Jedi]] [[Rael Averross]] spoke with a strong [[Ringo Vinda]]n accent that he never lost while growing up on Coruscant.<ref name="Master and Apprentice" /> The [[Fighting pit|pit fighter]] [[Tasu Leech]], who considered Basic a weak language for weak people<ref name="Tasu Databank">{{Databank|tasu-leech|Tasu Leech}}</ref> and instead spoke in [[Jablogian]],<ref name="Bounty Hunters 8">[[Bounty Hunters 8|''Bounty Hunters'' 8]]</ref> did at times use Basic in his younger years. His Basic came out with a thick [[Nar Kanji]] accent, which the [[bounty hunter]] [[Dengar]] mocked him for, calling it a "low-class accent."<ref name="Bounty Hunters 24">[[Bounty Hunters 24|''Bounty Hunters'' 24]]</ref>

{{Language-stub}}

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|To make peace with it: it's never literal language we're hearing. Best to think of it as a period piece modernized for our ears. Basic doesn't sound like English. And the words of a foreign dub are just as "canon" as the English one.|Pablo Hidalgo's opinion on how to perceive Basic.|<ref name="English Pablo">{{Bluesky|username=infinata.bsky.social|url=post/3lmiixjgfx22n|name=[[Pablo Hidalgo]]|date=2025-04-10|quote=To make peace with it: it’s never literal language we’re hearing. Best to think of it as a period piece modernized for our ears. Basic doesn’t sound like English. And the words of a foreign dub are just as “canon” as the English one.|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/rK8AW}}</ref>}}
Basic is the name given to the [[Wikipedia:English language|English language]] in the ''Star Wars'' saga, although in dubbed and translated versions of the series it will for all intents and purposes resemble those languages. As a result, Basic comes in as many accents as those of the actors in the films, television series and video games. For example, when she filmed the original [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']], [[Carrie Fisher]] spoke with [[Wikipedia:Received Pronunciation|Received Pronunciation]] during her first day of shooting (which was the scene where Leia confronts Wilhuff Tarkin). "I had a British accent," she explained. "Who could say those lines? 'I thought I recognized your foul stench when I was brought on board.' What? Say that like an American and I'll pay you."<ref>{{WebCite|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/carrie-fisher-british-accent-star-wars-article-1.2457675|text=Carrie Fisher explains in simple English why she speaks with a British accent in part of 'Star Wars'|author=Sacks, Ethan|date=2015-12-07|work=New York Daily News|archivedate=20181225070711}}</ref>

The book [[Bloodline (novel)|''Bloodline'']] identifies Tarkin's accent and that of other senior Imperial officers as aristocratic,<ref name="Bloodline" /> as such [[Wookieepedia]] treats all characters speaking with a Received Pronunciation British accent, as Tarkin does in ''A New Hope'', as having an aristocratic accent.<ref name="A New Hope">{{Film|IV}}</ref> The audiobooks of ''[[Aftermath: Empire's End]]'' and ''[[Battlefront: Twilight Company]]'' establishes that the Chandrilan accent and Coruscanti accent respectively are both also the aristocratic Received Pronunciation.<ref name="Empire's End" /><ref name="Twilight Company" /> Indeed, the accent of Lorth Needa, portrayed by British actor [[Michael Culver]] in [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''Star Wars'': Episode V ''The Empire Strikes Back'']],<ref name="Empire Strikes Back">{{Film|V}}</ref> was identified as a Core Worlds accent in the short story "[[Amara Kel's Rules for TIE Pilot Survival (Probably)]]."<ref name="TIE Pilot Survival" /> The real-world Scottish accent used by Bala-Tik in [[Star Wars: Episode VII The Force Awakens|''Star Wars'': Episode VII ''The Force Awakens'']]<ref name="TFA">{{Film|VII}}</ref> is described as a Core Worlds accent with a harsher edge in ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens: The Visual Dictionary]]''.<ref name="TFA dictionary" /> ''[[Master & Apprentice]]'' describes Rael Aveross's real world southern American drawl as a Ringo Vindan accent.<ref name="Master and Apprentice" />

While reflecting over what real world terms can be used as ''Star Wars'' terminology and what cannot,<ref name="Cockpit Pablo">{{Bluesky|username=infinata.bsky.social|url=post/3lmiisghqsk2n|name=[[Pablo Hidalgo]]|date=2025-04-10|quote=Editing the Star Wars-iness of text is an idiosyncratic art and not a defined science. I balk at the use of “footage” due to its outdated terrestrial origins, but we’ve all given “cockpit” a pass because it’s so grandfathered in.|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/a1m1v}}</ref> Lore Advisor [[Pablo Hidalgo]] urged fans to not think of what they hear in ''Star Wars'' media as the literal language. Instead, he believes that in-universe Basic does not actually sound like real-world English, with Hidalgo instead comparing ''Star Wars'' content to a modernized period piece.<ref name="English Pablo" /> To further explain this concept, he pointed to the HBO Western drama [[Wikipedia:Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]], which uses modern swears for the sake of the audience instead of period-accurate language.<ref name="Deadwood Pablo">{{Bluesky|username=infinata.bsky.social|url=post/3lmijb2ojzk2n|name=[[Pablo Hidalgo]]|date=2025-04-10|quote=A related example — the swears in Deadwood aren’t period accurate, because the period accurate swears wouldn’t really land for modern viewers. So, that gets modernized, and we’re all grateful for it.|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/B1vq9}}</ref>

